$ Oracle: Virtual columns

{ Virtual columns vs default values

  Default values are used to provide a value in → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/DML/insert[insert statements] in absence of an explicitely given value:
code {
create table tq84_virt_col_t (
   id           number(5),
   default_val  date  default sysdate
);

insert into tq84_virt_col_t (id) values (1);
code }

  On the other hand, a virtual column provides a value at query time:
code {
create or replace view tq84_virt_col_v as
select
   t.id,
   t.default_val,
   sysdate as virtual_val
from
   tq84_virt_col_t t
;

select
   *
from
   tq84_virt_col_v;
code }

  Cleaning up:
code {
drop view  tq84_virt_col_v;
drop table tq84_virt_col_t;
code }

}
{ Querying virtual columns from the data dictionary

  The expression that provides the value for a virtual column can be queried from the column `data_default` in the → development/databases/Oracle/installed/data-dictionary[data dictionary's] view
 `→ development/databases/Oracle/installed/data-dictionary/tab/cols`:
code {
select
   obj.object_type,
   obj.owner,
   col.table_name,
   col.column_name,
   col.data_default,
   col.*
from
   → development/databases/Oracle/installed/data-dictionary/objects   obj                                          join
   → development/databases/Oracle/installed/data-dictionary/tab/cols  col  on obj.owner       = col.owner      and
                         obj.object_name = col.table_name
where
-- obj.oracle_maintained = 'N'                              and
   col.table_name in ('TQ84_VIRT_COL_V', 'TQ84_VIRT_COL_T') and
   col.owner      = user
;
code }

}
